# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: postscript-lang
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] It has historically specialized in software for the creation and publication of a wide range of content, including graphics, photography, illustration, animation, multimedia/video, motion pictures and print.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Its flagship products include Adobe Photoshop image editing software; Adobe Illustrator vector-based illustration software; Adobe Acrobat and the Portable Document Format (PDF); and a host of tools primarily for audio-visual content creation, editing, and publishing.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Adobe offered a bundled solution of its products named Adobe Creative Suite, which evolved into a subscription-based offering named Adobe Creative Cloud.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] The company also expanded into digital marketing software and in 2021 was considered one of the top global leaders in Customer Experience Management (CXM).
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Adobe was founded in December 1982 by John Warnock and Charles Geschke, who established the company after leaving Xerox PARC to develop and sell the PostScript page description language.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] In 1985, Apple Computer licensed PostScript for use in its LaserWriter printers, which helped spark the desktop publishing revolution.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] As of 2022, Adobe had more than 26,000 employees worldwide.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Adobe also has major development operations in the United States in Newton, New York City, Arden Hills, Lehi, Seattle, Austin and San Francisco.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] It also has major development operations in Noida and Bangalore in India.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] The company was started in John Warnock's garage.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] The name of the company, Adobe, comes from Adobe Creek in Los Altos, California, a stream which ran behind Warnock's house.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] The creek is named because of the type of clay found there (Adobe being a Spanish word for *Mudbrick*).
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Adobe's corporate logo features a stylized "A" and was designed by graphic designer Marva Warnock, John Warnock's wife.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Steve Jobs attempted to buy the company for $5 million in 1982, but Warnock and Geschke refused.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Their investors urged them to work something out with Jobs, so they agreed to sell him shares worth 19 percent of the company.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Jobs paid a five-times multiple of their company's valuation at the time, plus a five-year license fee for PostScript, in advance.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] The purchase and advance made Adobe the first company in the history of Silicon Valley to become profitable in its first year.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Warnock and Geschke considered various business options including a copy-service business and a turnkey system for office printing.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Then it chose to focus on developing specialized printing software and created the Adobe PostScript page description language.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] PostScript was the first international standard for computer printing as it included algorithms describing the letter-forms of many languages.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Adobe added kanji printer products in 1988.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Warnock and Geschke were also able to bolster the credibility of PostScript by connecting with a typesetting manufacturer.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] They weren't able to work with Compugraphic, but then worked with Linotype to license the Helvetica and Times Roman fonts (through the Linotron 100).
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] By 1987, PostScript had become the industry-standard printer language with more than 400 third-party software programs and licensing agreements with 19 printer companies.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Adobe's first products after PostScript were digital fonts which they released in a proprietary format called Type 1, worked on by Bill Paxton after he left Stanford.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Apple subsequently developed a competing standard, TrueType, which provided full scalability and precise control of the pixel pattern created by the font's outlines, and licensed it to Microsoft.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Starting in the mid-1980s, Adobe entered the consumer software market, starting with Adobe Illustrator, a vector-based drawing program for the Apple Macintosh.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Illustrator, which grew out of the firm's in-house font-development software, helped popularize PostScript-enabled laser printers.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] By the mid-1990s, Adobe would acquire Photoshop from John and Thomas Knoll, FrameMaker from Frame Technology Corporation, and After Effects and PageMaker from Aldus, as well as develop Adobe Premiere, later known as Premiere Pro, in-house, initially releasing it in 1991.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Around the same time as the development of Illustrator, Adobe entered the NASDAQ Composite index in August 1986.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] In 1993, Adobe introduced the Portable Document Format, commonly shortened to the initialism PDF, and its Adobe Acrobat and Reader software.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Warnock originally developed the PDF under a code name, "The Camelot Project", using PostScript technology to create a widely available digital document format, able to display text, raster graphics, vector graphics, and fonts.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Adobe kept the PDF as a proprietary file format from its introduction until 2008, when the PDF became an ISO international standard under ISO number ISO 32000-1:2008, though the PDF file format was free for viewers since its introduction.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] With its acquisition of Aldus, in addition to gaining PageMaker and After Effects, Adobe gained control over the TIFF file format for images.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] The 2000s saw various developments for the company.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Its first notable acquisition in the decade was in 2002, when Adobe acquired Canadian company Accelio, also known as JetForm.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] In May 2003, Adobe purchased audio editing and multitrack recording software Cool Edit Pro from Syntrillium Software for $16.5 million, as well as a large loop library called "Loopology".
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Adobe then renamed Cool Edit Pro to Adobe Audition.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] It was in 2003 that the company introduced the first version of Adobe Creative Suite, bundling its creative software into a single package.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] By April 2008, Adobe released Adobe Media Player.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] On April 27, Adobe discontinued the development and sales of its older HTML/web development software, GoLive, in favor of Dreamweaver.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Adobe offered a discount on Dreamweaver for GoLive users and supports those who still use GoLive with online tutorials and migration assistance.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] On June 1, Adobe launched Acrobat.com, a series of web applications geared for collaborative work.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Creative Suite 4, which includes Design, Web, Production Premium, and Master Collection came out in October 2008 in six configurations at prices from about US$1,700 to $2,500 or by individual application.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] The Windows version of Photoshop includes 64-bit processing.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] On December 3, 2008, Adobe laid off 600 of its employees (8% of the worldwide staff) citing the weak economic environment.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] On September 15, 2009, Adobe Systems announced that it would acquire online marketing and web analytics company Omniture for $1.8 billion.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] The deal was completed on October 23, 2009.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Former Omniture products were integrated into the Adobe Marketing Cloud.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] On November 10, 2009, the company laid off a further 680 employees.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Adobe's 2010 was marked by continuing arguments with Apple over the latter's non-support for Adobe Flash on its iPhone, iPad and other products.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Former Apple CEO Steve Jobs claimed that Flash was not reliable or secure enough, while Adobe executives have argued that Apple wishes to maintain control over the iOS platform.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] In April 2010, Steve Jobs published a post titled *Thoughts on Flash* where he outlined his thoughts on Flash and the rise of HTML5.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] In January 2011, Adobe acquired DemDex, Inc. with the intent of adding DemDex's audience-optimization software to its online marketing suite.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] At Photoshop World 2011, Adobe unveiled a new mobile photo service.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Carousel was a new application for iPhone, iPad, and Mac that used Photoshop Lightroom technology to allow users to adjust and fine-tune images on all platforms.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Carousel also allowed users to automatically sync, share and browse photos.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] The service was later renamed "Adobe Revel".
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Later that same year in October, Adobe acquired Nitobi Software, the maker of the mobile application development framework *PhoneGap*.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] As part of the acquisition, the source code of PhoneGap was submitted to the Apache Foundation, where it became Apache Cordova.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] In November 2011, Adobe announced that it would cease development of Flash for mobile devices following version 11.1.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Instead, it would focus on HTML5 for mobile devices.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] In December 2011, Adobe announced that it had entered into a definitive agreement to acquire privately held Efficient Frontier.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] In December 2012, Adobe opened a new 280,000-square-foot (26,000 m2) corporate campus in Lehi, Utah.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] In 2013, Adobe endured a major security breach.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Vast portions of the source code for the company's software were stolen and posted online and over 150 million records of Adobe's customers were made readily available for download.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] In 2012, about 40 million sets of payment card information were compromised by a hack at Adobe.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] A class-action lawsuit alleging that the company suppressed employee compensation was filed against Adobe, and three other Silicon Valley–based companies in a California federal district court in 2013.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] In May 2014, it was revealed the four companies, Adobe, Apple, Google, and Intel had reached an agreement with the plaintiffs, 64,000 employees of the four companies, to pay a sum of $324.5 million to settle the suit.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] 2011 saw the company first introduce Adobe Creative Cloud, a $600/year subscription plan to its creative software as opposed to a one-time perpetual license payment which could often top $2000 for creative professionals.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Reception to the mandatory subscriptions for future Adobe software was mostly negative, despite some positive testimonies on the move from customers and Adobe's attraction of 500,000 Creative Cloud subscribers by the service's first year.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] In March 2018, at Adobe Summit, the company and Nvidia announced their association to upgrade their AI and profound learning innovations.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] They planned to streamline Adobe Sensei AI and machine learning structure for Nvidia GPUs.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Adobe and Nvidia had cooperated for 10 years on GPU quickening.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] This incorporates Sensei-powered features, e.g. auto lip-sync in Adobe Character Animator CC and face-aware editing in Photoshop CC, and also cloud-based AI/ML items and features, for example, picture investigation for Adobe Stock and Lightroom CC and auto-labeling in Adobe Experience Supervisor.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Adobe further spent its time from 2018 to 2023 acquiring more companies to boost both Creative Cloud and the Adobe Experience Cloud, a software suite which increased business.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] These included e-commerce services provider Magento Commerce from private equity firm Permira for $1.68 billion in June 2018, Marketo for $4.75 billion in 2018, Allegorithmic in 2019 for just under $160 million, and Workfront in December 2020 for $1.5 billion.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] 2021 additionally saw Adobe add payment services to its e-commerce platforms in an attempt to compete with Shopify, accepting both credit cards and PayPal.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] In July 2020, as the United States presidential elections approached, the software giant imposed a ban on the political ads features on its digital advertising sales platform.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] On November 9, 2020, Adobe announced it would spend US$1.5 billion to acquire Workfront, a provider of marketing collaboration software.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] The acquisition was completed in early December 2020.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] On August 19, 2021, Adobe announced it had entered into a definitive agreement to acquire Frame.io, a leading cloud-based video collaboration platform.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] The transaction is valued at $1.275 billion and closed during the fourth quarter of Adobe's 2021 fiscal year.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Adobe announced a $20 billion acquisition of Figma, an Adobe XD competitor, in September 2022, its largest to date.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Regulatory scrutiny from the US and European Union began shortly after due to concerns that Adobe, already a major player in the design software market with XD, would have too much control if it also owned Figma.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] At the time of the announcement to acquire Figma, Adobe's share over the creative software market and design-software market was almost a monopoly.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] In December 2023, the two companies called off their merger, citing the regulatory challenges as a sign to both that the deal was not likely to be approved.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Adobe paid Figma a $1 billion termination fee per their merger agreement.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] On June 17, 2024, the US Federal Trade Commission together with the US Department of Justice filed a lawsuit against Adobe for its subscription business model practice, citing hidden termination fees and the company pushing customers towards more expensive plans.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] On March 13, 2026, the lawsuit was settled out of court for $150M.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] In June 2024, after facing backlash for its changes to the terms of service, Adobe updated them to explicitly pledge it will not use customer data to train its artificial intelligence models.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] In November 2025, Adobe Inc. announced its agreement to acquire Semrush for $1.9 billion.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] In March 2026, Adobe announced Shantanu Narayen would step down from his position as CEO after 18 years.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Narayen was expected to stay on until a new CEO was identified and remain as chairman.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Adobe, among other software companies, were in investor crosshairs amid concerns about competitive threats from increased AI adoption.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] On March 16, 2026, Adobe and NVIDIA announced a strategic partnership to deliver next-generation Adobe Firefly models and agentic workflows.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] The collaboration spans AI model development, 3D product visualization, document intelligence, and cloud media workflows, with a joint go-to-market strategy targeting enterprise customers through Adobe's Firefly Foundry platform.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Adobe Color, Photoshop Express, Acrobat.com, Behance and Adobe Express.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] A microstock agency that presently provides over 57 million high-resolution, royalty-free images and videos available to license (via subscription or credit purchase methods).
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] In 2015, Adobe acquired **Fotolia**, a stock content marketplace founded in 2005 by Thibaud Elziere, Oleg Tscheltzoff, and Patrick Chassany which operated in 23 countries.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] It was run as a stand-alone website until 2019, but has since been integrated into Adobe Stock.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] A family of content, development, and customer relationship management products, with what Adobe calls the "next generation" of its Sensei artificial intelligence and machine learning framework, introduced in March 2019.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Adobe has been criticized for its pricing practices, with retail prices being up to twice as much in non-US countries.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] After Adobe revealed the pricing for the Creative Suite 3 Master Collection, which was £1,000 higher for European customers, a petition to protest over "unfair pricing" was published and signed by 10,000 users.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] In June 2009, Adobe further increased its prices in the UK by 10% in spite of weakening of the pound against the dollar, and UK users were not allowed to buy from the US store.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Adobe's Reader and Flash programs were listed on "The 10 most hated programs of all time" article by *TechRadar*.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Hackers have exploited vulnerabilities in Adobe programs, such as Adobe Reader, to gain unauthorized access to computers.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Adobe's Flash Player has also been criticized for, among other things, suffering from performance, memory usage and security problems.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] A report by security researchers from Kaspersky Lab criticized Adobe for producing the products having top 10 security vulnerabilities.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Observers noted that Adobe was spying on its customers by including spyware in the Creative Suite 3 software and quietly sending user data to a firm named Omniture.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] When users became aware, Adobe explained what the suspicious software did and admitted that they: "could and should do a better job taking security concerns into account".
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] When a security flaw was later discovered in Photoshop CS5, Adobe sparked outrage by saying it would leave the flaw unpatched, so anyone who wanted to use the software securely would have to pay for an upgrade.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Following a fierce backlash Adobe decided to provide the software patch.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Adobe has been criticized for pushing unwanted software including third-party browser toolbars and free virus scanners, usually as part of the Flash update process, and for pushing a third-party scareware program designed to scare users into paying for unneeded system repairs.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] On October 3, 2013, the company initially revealed that 2.9 million customers' sensitive and personal data was stolen in a security breach which included encrypted credit card information.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Adobe later admitted that 38 million active users have been affected and the attackers obtained access to their IDs and encrypted passwords, as well as to many inactive Adobe accounts.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] The company did not make it clear if all the personal information was encrypted, such as email addresses and physical addresses, though data privacy laws in 44 states require this information to be encrypted.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] In late 2013 a 3.8 GB file stolen from Adobe and containing 152 million usernames, reversibly encrypted passwords and unencrypted password hints was posted on AnonNews.org.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] LastPass, a password security firm, said that Adobe failed to use best practices for securing the passwords and has not salted them.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Another security firm, Sophos, showed that Adobe used a weak encryption method permitting the recovery of a lot of information with very little effort.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] According to IT expert Simon Bain, Adobe has failed its customers and 'should hang their heads in shame'.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Many of the credit cards were tied to the Creative Cloud software-by-subscription service.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Adobe offered its affected US customers a free membership in a credit monitoring service, but no similar arrangements have been made for non-US customers.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] When a data breach occurs in the US, penalties depend on the state where the victim resides, not where the company is based.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] After stealing the customers' data, cyber-thieves also accessed Adobe's source code repository, likely in mid-August 2013.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Because hackers acquired copies of the source code of Adobe proprietary products, they could find and exploit any potential weaknesses in its security, computer experts warned.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Security researcher Alex Holden, chief information security officer of Hold Security, characterized this Adobe breach, which affected Acrobat, ColdFusion and numerous other applications, as "one of the worst in US history".
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Adobe also announced that hackers stole parts of the source code of Photoshop, which according to commentators could allow programmers to copy its engineering techniques and would make it easier to pirate Adobe's expensive products.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Published on a server of a Russian-speaking hacker group, the "disclosure of encryption algorithms, other security schemes, and software vulnerabilities can be used to bypass protections for individual and corporate data" and may have opened the gateway to new generation zero-day attacks.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Hackers already used ColdFusion exploits to make off with usernames and encrypted passwords of PR Newswire's customers, which has been tied to the Adobe security breach.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] They also used a ColdFusion exploit to breach Washington state court and expose up to 200,000 Social Security numbers.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] In 1994, Adobe acquired Aldus Corp., a software vendor that sold FreeHand, a competing product.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] FreeHand was direct competition to Adobe Illustrator, Adobe's flagship vector-graphics editor.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] The Federal Trade Commission (FTC) intervened and forced Adobe to sell FreeHand back to Altsys, and also banned Adobe from buying back FreeHand or any similar program for the next 10 years (1994–2004).
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Altsys was then bought by Macromedia, which released versions 5 to 11.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] When Adobe acquired Macromedia in December 2005, it stalled development of FreeHand in 2007, effectively rendering it obsolete.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] With FreeHand and Illustrator, Adobe controlled the only two products that competed in the professional illustration program market for Macintosh operating systems.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] In 2011, a group of 5,000 FreeHand graphic designers convened under the banner *Free FreeHand*, and filed a civil antitrust complaint in the US District Court for the Northern District of California against Adobe.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Adobe had no response to the claims and the lawsuit was eventually settled.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] The FreeHand community believes Adobe should release the product to an open-source community if it cannot update it internally.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Adobe's software FTP server still contains a directory for FreeHand, but it is empty.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] In April 2021, Adobe received criticism from Twitter users for the company's cancellation fees after a customer shared a tweet showing they had been charged a $291.45 cancellation fee for their Adobe Creative Cloud subscription.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Many also showed their cancellation fees for Adobe Creative Cloud, with this leading to many encouraging piracy of Adobe products and/or purchase of alternatives with lower prices or using free and open-source software instead.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Furthermore, there have been reports that with changing subscriptions it is possible to avoid paying this fee.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Department of Justice and the FTC filed a lawsuit against Adobe and two of its executives in June 2024, alleging that the company's deceptive subscription practices and cancellation policies violated the Restore Online Shoppers' Confidence Act.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] According to the lawsuit, the company purportedly used small text disclosures, optional input fields, and complex web of links to obscure a concealed early termination fee.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] This fee reportedly amounted to fifty percent of the remaining value of annual contracts for users who chose to cancel early in the first year, resulting in significant penalties.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Customers who tried to cancel services by contacting customer service faced obstacles, including dropped calls and multiple transfers between representatives; others continued to be billed by Adobe, under the mistaken belief that they had successfully ended their subscriptions.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] In March 2026, Adobe agreed to pay $75 million to settle a lawsuit with the U.S.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Department of Justice over allegations that the company failed to clearly disclose cancellation fees associated with its subscription plans.
[src:postscript-lang/adobe-systems] Adobe responded the following day clarifying that it will not use user data to train generative AI or take users work as its own; however, it neglected to respond to the part in the TOS that gives Adobe the ability to view or use work that is contracted under an NDA.
[src:postscript-lang/document-structuring-conventions] The need for a structuring convention arises since PostScript is a Turing-complete programming language.
[src:postscript-lang/document-structuring-conventions] There is thus no guaranteed method — short of actually printing the document — to do things like determining how many pages long a given document is or how large a given page is, or how to skip to a particular page.
[src:postscript-lang/document-structuring-conventions] The addition of structure, with DSC comments exposing that structure, helps provide a way for, e.g., an intelligent print spooler to have the ability to rearrange the pages for printing, or for a page layout program to find the bounding box of a PostScript file used as a graphic image.
[src:postscript-lang/document-structuring-conventions] Collectively, any such program that takes PostScript files as input data is called a *document manager*.
[src:postscript-lang/document-structuring-conventions] In order for a PostScript print file to properly distill to PDF using Adobe tools, it should conform to basic DSC standards.
[src:postscript-lang/document-structuring-conventions] Some DSC comments serve a second function, specifying a way to tell the document manager to do certain things, like inserting a font or other PostScript code (collectively called *resources*) into the file.
[src:postscript-lang/document-structuring-conventions] DSC comments that serve this second function are more akin to preprocessing directives and are not purely comments.
[src:postscript-lang/document-structuring-conventions] Documents using those kinds of DSC comments require a functioning document manager to come out as intended; sending them directly to a printer will not work.
[src:postscript-lang/document-structuring-conventions] DSC is the basis for Encapsulated PostScript (EPS): EPS files are documents that conform to the DSC standards with further restrictions.
[src:postscript-lang/document-structuring-conventions] The set of DSC comments can be expanded by a mechanism called the Open Structuring Conventions, which, together with the EPS specification, form the basis of early versions of the Adobe Illustrator Artwork file format.
[src:postscript-lang/document-structuring-conventions] The basic premise of DSC is the separation of *prolog* (static definitions) and *script* (code that affects job-specific printed output), plus the disallowing of certain PostScript operators deemed inappropriate for page descriptions.
[src:postscript-lang/document-structuring-conventions] This ensures a basic level of predictability in the PostScript code, thus forming the basis of document manageability.
[src:postscript-lang/document-structuring-conventions] An optional, additional layer of document manageability is provided by separating the script into a *document setup* section, zero or more functionally independent *pages*, and an optional *trailer* (cleanup code).
[src:postscript-lang/document-structuring-conventions] This imposed structure is then exposed by delimiting the PostScript file with *DSC comments*, which normally begin with two percent signs followed by a keyword.
[src:postscript-lang/document-structuring-conventions] Some keywords need to be followed by a colon, an optional space character, and then a series of arguments.
[src:postscript-lang/document-structuring-conventions] Finally, the document is marked as conforming by starting it with a comment starting with “%!PS-Adobe-” followed by the DSC version number.
[src:postscript-lang/document-structuring-conventions] Sections of reusable PostScript code can be modularized into *procsets* (procedure sets, corresponding to function libraries in other programming languages), in order to ease the generation of PostScript code.
[src:postscript-lang/document-structuring-conventions] Procsets and other PostScript resources (for example, fonts) can be omitted from the PostScript file itself, and externally referenced by a directive-like DSC comment; such external referencing, however, can only work with a document manager that understands such DSC comments.
[src:postscript-lang/document-structuring-conventions] DSC version 3.0 was released on September 25, 1992.
[src:postscript-lang/encapsulated-postscript] In short, EPS files are self-contained, reasonably predictable PostScript documents that describe an image or drawing and can be placed within another PostScript document.
[src:postscript-lang/encapsulated-postscript] An EPS file is essentially a PostScript program, saved as a single file that includes a low-resolution preview "encapsulated" within it, allowing some programs to display a preview on the screen.
[src:postscript-lang/encapsulated-postscript] An EPS file contains a DSC comment describing the rectangle containing the image.
[src:postscript-lang/encapsulated-postscript] Applications can use this information to lay out the page, even if they are unable to directly render the PostScript inside.
[src:postscript-lang/encapsulated-postscript] EPS files frequently include a preview picture of the content for on-screen display.
[src:postscript-lang/encapsulated-postscript] The idea is to allow a simple preview of the final output in any application that can draw a bitmap.
[src:postscript-lang/encapsulated-postscript] Without this preview, the applications would have to directly render the PostScript (PS) data inside the EPS, which was beyond the capabilities of most machines that used PostScript.
[src:postscript-lang/encapsulated-postscript] When EPS was first implemented, the only machines widely using PostScript were Apple Macintoshes.
[src:postscript-lang/encapsulated-postscript] These machines could not directly render the PostScript, which presented Adobe with the dilemma of how to provide a preview image for the designer while also including the PS version for the printer.
[src:postscript-lang/encapsulated-postscript] On the Mac this turned out to be easy to solve, as the Mac file system includes two parts (known as *forks*) that are logically referred to as one file.
[src:postscript-lang/encapsulated-postscript] By placing the PostScript in the data fork and a standard Mac PICT resource in the resource fork, both images could be moved about together invisibly as if they were one file.
[src:postscript-lang/encapsulated-postscript] While a PICT preview often contains a bitmap, it could also contain a vector representation of the whole image, providing very high quality previews.
[src:postscript-lang/encapsulated-postscript] Neither of these technologies is commonly used on any other operating system, however.
[src:postscript-lang/encapsulated-postscript] When faced with the same problems on Microsoft Windows-based versions of their programs, Adobe chose to instead add a TIFF file encoded into the header section of the PostScript.
[src:postscript-lang/encapsulated-postscript] Sometimes, although more rarely, they used the Windows Metafile (WMF) format instead.
[src:postscript-lang/encapsulated-postscript] WMF has the potential to provide vector previews, similar to PICT on the Mac.
[src:postscript-lang/encapsulated-postscript] Both of these PC format EPS files have a particular disadvantage: because the PostScript data, header, and preview are all in the same file, they will cause printing errors if a program does not understand the format well enough to extract only the PostScript data.
[src:postscript-lang/encapsulated-postscript] A fourth format known as a *EPSI* includes an ASCII-encoded preview bitmap.
[src:postscript-lang/encapsulated-postscript] This format provides only black-and-white previews.
[src:postscript-lang/encapsulated-postscript] With several different ways of representing the preview, EPSI files have limited portability.
[src:postscript-lang/encapsulated-postscript] An application that is unable to interpret an EPS file's preview will typically show an empty box on screen, but it will be able to print the file correctly.
[src:postscript-lang/encapsulated-postscript] The most widely supported kind of preview is a Windows format preview with a TIFF.
[src:postscript-lang/encapsulated-postscript] Due to the ability to use embedded scripts, Microsoft removed support for EPS files in Microsoft Office programs in May 2018.
[src:postscript-lang/ghostscript] Ghostscript can be used as a raster image processor (RIP) for raster computer printers—for instance, as an input filter of line printer daemon—or as the RIP engine behind PostScript and PDF viewers.
[src:postscript-lang/ghostscript] It can also be used as a file format converter, such as PostScript to PDF converter.
[src:postscript-lang/ghostscript] The `ps2pdf` conversion program comes with the Ghostscript distribution.
[src:postscript-lang/ghostscript] Ghostscript can also serve as the back-end for PDF to raster image (png, tiff, jpeg, etc.) converter; this is often combined with a PostScript printer driver in "virtual printer" PDF creators.
[src:postscript-lang/ghostscript] As it takes the form of a language interpreter, Ghostscript can also be used as a general purpose programming environment.
[src:postscript-lang/ghostscript] Ghostscript has been ported to many operating systems, including Unix-like systems, classic Mac OS, OpenVMS, Microsoft Windows, Plan 9, MS-DOS, FreeDOS, OS/2, ArcaOS, Atari TOS, RISC OS and AmigaOS.
[src:postscript-lang/ghostscript] Ghostscript was originally written by L.
[src:postscript-lang/ghostscript] Peter Deutsch for the GNU Project, and released under the GNU General Public License in 1988.
[src:postscript-lang/ghostscript] At the time of the initial release there was a similar commercial software product named GoScript from LaserGo.
[src:postscript-lang/ghostscript] With version 8.54 in 2006, both development branches were merged again, and dual-licensed releases were still provided.
[src:postscript-lang/ghostscript] Ghostscript is currently owned by Artifex Software and maintained by Artifex Software employees and the worldwide user community.
[src:postscript-lang/ghostscript] According to Artifex, as of version 9.03, the commercial version of Ghostscript can no longer be freely distributed for commercial purposes without purchasing a license, though the (A)GPL variant allows commercial distribution provided all code using it is released under the (A)GPL.
[src:postscript-lang/ghostscript] In February 2013, with version 9.07, Ghostscript changed its license from GPLv3 to GNU AGPL. which raised license compatibility questions, for example by Debian.
[src:postscript-lang/ghostscript] Starting with release 9.55.0 Ghostscript has two built-in PDF interpreters.
[src:postscript-lang/ghostscript] Until spring 2022, up to Ghostscript version 9.56.1, the default PDF interpreters implementation itself was coded in PostScript.
[src:postscript-lang/ghostscript] The new default PDF interpreter has been rewritten in C entirely, and is faster and more secure than its predecessor, while its interface and graphics library have not changed.
[src:postscript-lang/ghostscript] Scripting the new C written PDF interpreter from PostScript is still possible.
[src:postscript-lang/ghostscript] There are several sets of free fonts supplied for Ghostscript, intended to be metrically compatible with common fonts attached with the PostScript standard.
[src:postscript-lang/ghostscript] The Ghostscript fonts were developed in the PostScript Type 1 format but have been converted into the TrueType format.
[src:postscript-lang/ghostscript] As a result, a user can install and use the Ghostscript fonts via most modern software.
[src:postscript-lang/ghostscript] Furthermore, the Ghostscript fonts are used as parts of various open source applications, e.g., the Linux version of GIMP depends on Graphviz which in turn depends on the Ghostscript fonts.
[src:postscript-lang/ghostscript] Finally, multiple open source font projects used glyphs from the Ghostscript fonts, e.g., the Latin characters of GNU FreeFont are based on Nimbus Mono L, Nimbus Roman No9 L, and Nimbus Sans L.
[src:postscript-lang/ghostscript] The TeX Gyre fonts are also based on 8 out of the 10 original Ghostscript typeface families.
[src:postscript-lang/ghostscript] The Garamond font has additionally been improved upon.
[src:postscript-lang/page-description-language] In digital printing, a **page description language** (**PDL**) is a computer language that describes the appearance of a printed page in a higher level than an actual output bitmap (or generally raster graphics).
[src:postscript-lang/page-description-language] An overlapping term is **printer control language**, which includes Hewlett-Packard's Printer Command Language (PCL).
[src:postscript-lang/page-description-language] PostScript is one of the most noted page description languages.
[src:postscript-lang/page-description-language] The markup language adaptation of the PDL is the page description markup language.
[src:postscript-lang/page-description-language] Page description languages are text (human-readable) or binary data streams, usually intermixed with text or graphics to be printed.
[src:postscript-lang/page-description-language] They are distinct from graphics application programming interfaces (APIs) such as GDI and OpenGL that can be called by software to generate graphical output.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] PDF has its roots in "The Camelot Project" initiated by Adobe co-founder John Warnock in 1991.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] PDF was standardized as ISO 32000 in 2008.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] It is maintained by ISO TC 171 SC 2 WG8, of which the PDF Association is the committee manager.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The last edition as ISO 32000-2:2020 was published in December 2020.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] PDF files may contain a variety of content besides flat text and graphics including logical structuring elements, interactive elements such as annotations and form-fields, layers, rich media (including video content), three-dimensional objects using U3D or PRC, and various other data formats.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The PDF specification also provides for encryption and digital signatures, file attachments, and metadata to enable workflows requiring these features.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The development of PDF began in 1991 when John Warnock wrote a paper for a project then code-named Camelot, in which he proposed the creation of a simplified version of PostScript called Interchange PostScript (IPS).
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Unlike traditional PostScript, which was tightly focused on rendering print jobs to output devices, IPS would be optimized for displaying pages to any screen and any platform.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Adobe made the PDF specification available free of charge in 1993.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] In the early years PDF was popular mainly in desktop publishing workflows, and competed with several other formats, including DjVu, Envoy, Common Ground Digital Paper, Farallon Replica and even Adobe's own PostScript format.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] PDF was a proprietary format controlled by Adobe until it was released as an open standard on July 1, 2008, and published by the International Organization for Standardization as ISO 32000-1:2008, at which time control of the specification passed to an ISO Committee of volunteer industry experts.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] In 2008, Adobe published a Public Patent License to ISO 32000-1 granting royalty-free rights for all patents owned by Adobe necessary to make, use, sell, and distribute PDF-compliant implementations.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] These proprietary technologies are not standardized, and their specification is published only on Adobe's website.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Many of them are not supported by third-party implementations of PDF.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] ISO published version 2.0 of PDF, ISO 32000-2 in 2017, replacing the specification provided by Adobe.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] In December 2020, the second edition of PDF 2.0, ISO 32000-2:2020, was published, with clarifications, corrections, and critical updates to normative references ISO 32000-2 does not include any proprietary technologies as normative references.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] In April 2023 the PDF Association made ISO 32000-2 available for download free of charge.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] A PDF file is often a combination of vector graphics, text, and bitmap graphics.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] In later PDF revisions, a PDF document can also support links (inside document or web page), forms, JavaScript (initially available as a plugin for Acrobat 3.0), or any other types of embedded contents that can be handled using plug-ins.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] PostScript is a page description language run in an interpreter to generate an image.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] It can handle graphics and has standard features of programming languages such as branching and looping.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] PDF is a subset of PostScript, simplified to remove certain control flow features, while graphics commands remain.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] PostScript was not intended for long-term storage and real-time interactive rendering of electronic documents to computer monitors, so there was no need to support anything other than consecutive rendering of pages.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] If there was an error in the final printed output, the user would correct it at the application level and send a new print job in the form of an entirely new PostScript file.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Traditionally, to go from PostScript to PDF, a source PostScript file (that is, an executable program) is used as the basis for generating PostScript-like PDF code (see, e.g., Adobe Distiller).
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] This is done by applying standard compiler techniques like loop unrolling, inlining and removing unused branches, resulting in code that is purely declarative and static.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The result is then packaged into a container format, together with all necessary dependencies for correct rendering (external files, graphics, or fonts to which the document refers), and compressed.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] PDF since v1.6 supports embedding of interactive 3D documents: 3D drawings can be embedded using U3D or PRC and various other data formats.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] A PDF file is organized using ASCII characters, except for certain elements that may have binary content.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The file starts with a header containing a magic number (as a readable string) and the version of the format, for example `%PDF-1.7`.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The format is a subset of a COS ("Carousel" Object Structure) format.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Comments using 8-bit characters prefixed with the percent sign (`%`) may be inserted.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Objects may be either *direct* (embedded in another object) or *indirect*.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Indirect objects are numbered with an *object number* and a *generation number* and defined between the `obj` and `endobj` keywords if residing in the document root.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Beginning with PDF version 1.5, indirect objects (except other streams) may also be located in special streams known as *object streams* (marked `/Type /ObjStm`).
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] This technique enables non-stream objects to have standard stream filters applied to them, reduces the size of files that have large numbers of small indirect objects and is especially useful for *Tagged PDF*.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Object streams do not support specifying an object's *generation number* (other than 0).
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] An index table, also called the cross-reference table, is located near the end of the file and gives the byte offset of each indirect object from the start of the file.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] This design allows for efficient random access to the objects in the file, and also allows for small changes to be made without rewriting the entire file (*incremental update*).
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Before PDF version 1.5, the table would always be in a special ASCII format, be marked with the `xref` keyword, and follow the main body composed of indirect objects.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Version 1.5 introduced optional *cross-reference streams*, which have the form of a standard stream object, possibly with filters applied.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Such a stream may be used instead of the ASCII cross-reference table and contains the offsets and other information in binary format.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The format is flexible in that it allows for integer width specification (using the `/W` array), so that for example, a document not exceeding 64 KiB in size may dedicate only 2 bytes for object offsets.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] To ensure backward compatibility, a hybrid-reference PDF file may include both traditional cross-reference tables and cross-reference streams, allowing older PDF processors to read the file while still taking advantage of the new features introduced in version 1.5.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Within each page, there are one or multiple content streams that describe the text, vector and images being drawn on the page.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The content stream is stack-based, similar to PostScript.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] There are two layouts to the PDF files: non-linearized (not "optimized") and linearized ("optimized").
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Non-linearized PDF files can be smaller than their linear counterparts, though they are slower to access because portions of the data required to assemble pages of the document are scattered throughout the PDF file.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] PDF files may be optimized using Adobe Acrobat software or QPDF.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Page dimensions are not limited by the format itself.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The basic design of how graphics are represented in PDF is very similar to that of PostScript, except for the use of transparency, which was added in PDF 1.4.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] PDF graphics use a device-independent Cartesian coordinate system to describe the surface of a page.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] A PDF page description can use a matrix to scale, rotate, or skew graphical elements.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] A key concept in PDF is that of the *graphics state*, which is a collection of graphical parameters that may be changed, saved, and restored by a *page description*.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] As in PostScript, vector graphics in PDF are constructed with *paths*.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Paths are usually composed of lines and cubic Bézier curves, but can also be constructed from the outlines of text.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Unlike PostScript, PDF does not allow a single path to mix text outlines with lines and curves.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Paths can be stroked, filled, filled then stroked, or used for clipping.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Strokes and fills can use any color set in the graphics state, including *patterns*.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The simplest is the *tiling pattern* in which a piece of artwork is specified to be drawn repeatedly.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] This may be a *colored tiling pattern*, with the colors specified in the pattern object, or an *uncolored tiling pattern*, which defers color specification to the time the pattern is drawn.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Beginning with PDF 1.3 there is also a *shading pattern*, which draws continuously varying colors.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] There are seven types of shading patterns of which the simplest are the *axial shading* (Type 2) and *radial shading* (Type 3).
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Raster images in PDF (called *Image XObjects*) are represented by dictionaries with an associated stream.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The dictionary describes the properties of the image, and the stream contains the image data.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] (Less commonly, small raster images may be embedded directly in a page description as an *inline image*.) Images are typically *filtered* for compression purposes.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Normally all image content in a PDF is embedded in the file.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] But PDF allows image data to be stored in external files by the use of *external streams* or *Alternate Images*.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Standardized subsets of PDF, including PDF/A and PDF/X, prohibit these features.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Text in PDF is represented by *text elements* in page content streams.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] A text element specifies that *characters* should be drawn at certain positions.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The characters are specified using the *encoding* of a selected *font resource*.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] A font object in PDF is a description of a digital typeface.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] It may either describe the characteristics of a typeface, or it may include an embedded *font file*.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The latter case is called an *embedded font* while the former is called an *unembedded font*.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The font files that may be embedded are based on widely used standard digital font formats: Type 1 (and its compressed variant CFF), TrueType, and (beginning with PDF 1.6) OpenType.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Additionally PDF supports the Type 3 variant in which the components of the font are described by PDF graphic operators.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] These fonts, or suitable substitute fonts with the same metrics, should be available in most PDF readers, but they are not *guaranteed* to be available in the reader, and may only display correctly if the system has them installed.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Fonts may be substituted if they are not embedded in a PDF.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Within text strings, characters are shown using *character codes* (integers) that map to glyphs in the current font using an *encoding*.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] There are several predefined encodings, including *WinAnsi*, *MacRoman*, and many encodings for East Asian languages and a font can have its own built-in encoding.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The encoding mechanisms in PDF were designed for Type 1 fonts, and the rules for applying them to TrueType fonts are complex.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] For large fonts or fonts with non-standard glyphs, the special encodings *Identity-H* (for horizontal writing) and *Identity-V* (for vertical) are used.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] With such fonts, it is necessary to provide a *ToUnicode* table if semantic information about the characters is to be preserved.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] A text document which is scanned to PDF without the text being recognised by optical character recognition (OCR) is an image, with no fonts or text properties.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The original imaging model of PDF was *opaque*, similar to PostScript, where each object drawn on the page completely replaced anything previously marked in the same location.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] In PDF 1.4 the imaging model was extended to allow transparency.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] When transparency is used, new objects interact with previously marked objects to produce blending effects.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The addition of transparency to PDF was done by means of new extensions that were designed to be ignored in products written to PDF 1.3 and earlier specifications.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] As a result, files that use a small amount of transparency might be viewed acceptably by older viewers, but files making extensive use of transparency could be viewed incorrectly by an older viewer.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The transparency extensions are based on the key concepts of *transparency groups*, *blending modes*, *shape*, and *alpha*.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The model is closely aligned with the features of Adobe Illustrator version 9.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The blend modes were based on those used by Adobe Photoshop at the time.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] When the PDF 1.4 specification was published, the formulas for calculating blend modes were kept secret by Adobe.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The concept of a transparency group in PDF specification is independent of existing notions of "group" or "layer" in applications such as Adobe Illustrator.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Those groupings reflect logical relationships among objects that are meaningful when editing those objects, but they are not part of the imaging model.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] A **tagged PDF** (see clause 14.8 in ISO 32000) includes document structure and semantics information to enable reliable text extraction and accessibility.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Technically speaking, tagged PDF is a stylized use of the format that builds on the logical structure framework introduced in PDF 1.3.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Tagged PDF defines a set of standard structure types and attributes that allow page content (text, graphics, and images) to be extracted and reused for other purposes.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Tagged PDF is not required in situations where a PDF file is intended only for print.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Since the feature is optional, and since the rules for tagged PDF were relatively vague in ISO 32000-1, support for tagged PDF among consuming devices, including assistive technology (AT), is uneven as of 2021.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] ISO 32000-2, however, includes an improved discussion of tagged PDF which is anticipated to facilitate further adoption.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] An ISO-standardized subset of PDF specifically targeted at accessibility, PDF/UA, was first published in 2012.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] With the introduction of PDF version 1.5 (2003) came the concept of Layers.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Layers, more formally known as Optional Content Groups (OCGs), refer to sections of content in a PDF document that can be selectively viewed or hidden by document authors or viewers.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] This capability is useful in CAD drawings, layered artwork, maps, multi-language documents, etc.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Basically, it consists of an Optional Content Properties Dictionary added to the document root.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] This dictionary contains an array of Optional Content Groups (OCGs), each describing a set of information and each of which may be individually displayed or suppressed, plus a set of Optional Content Configuration Dictionaries, which give the status (Displayed or Suppressed) of the given OCGs.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] A PDF file may be encrypted, for security, in which case a password is needed to view or edit the contents.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] PDF 2.0 defines 256-bit AES encryption as the standard for PDF 2.0 files.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The PDF Reference also defines ways that third parties can define their own encryption systems for PDF.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] PDF files may be digitally signed, to provide secure authentication; complete details on implementing digital signatures in PDF are provided in ISO 32000-2.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] PDF files may also contain embedded DRM restrictions that provide further controls that limit copying, editing, or printing.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] These restrictions depend on the reader software to obey them, so the security they provide is limited.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The user password encrypts the file, while the owner password does not, instead relying on client software to respect these restrictions.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] An owner password can easily be removed by software, including some free online services.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Thus, the use restrictions that a document author places on a PDF document are not secure, and cannot be assured once the file is distributed; this warning is displayed when applying such restrictions using Adobe Acrobat software to create or edit PDF files.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Even without removing the password, most freeware or open source PDF readers ignore the permission "protections" and allow the user to print or make copies of excerpts of the text as if the document were not limited by password protection.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Beginning with PDF 1.5, Usage rights (UR) signatures are used to enable additional interactive features that are not available by default in a particular PDF viewer application.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The signature is used to validate that the permissions have been granted by a bona fide granting authority.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] For example, Adobe Systems grants permissions to enable additional features in Adobe Reader, using public-key cryptography.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Adobe Reader verifies that the signature uses a certificate from an Adobe-authorized certificate authority.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Any PDF application can use this same mechanism for its own purposes.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Under specific circumstances including non-patched systems of the receiver, the information the receiver of a digital signed document sees can be manipulated by the sender after the document has been signed by the signer.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] PAdES (*PDF Advanced Electronic Signatures*) is a set of restrictions and extensions to PDF and ISO 32000-1 making it suitable for advanced electronic signatures.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] This is published by ETSI as TS 102 778.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] PDF files can have file attachments which processors may access and open or save to a local filesystem.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] PDF files can contain two types of metadata.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The first is the Document Information Dictionary, a set of key/value fields such as author, title, subject, creation and update dates.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] This is optional and is referenced from an `Info` key in the trailer of the file.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] A small set of fields is defined and can be extended with additional text values if required.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] In PDF 1.4, support was added for Metadata Streams, using the Extensible Metadata Platform (XMP) to add XML standards-based extensible metadata as used in other file formats.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] PDF 2.0 allows metadata to be attached to any object in the document, such as information about embedded illustrations, fonts, and images, as well as the whole document (attaching to the document catalog), using an extensible schema.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] PDF documents can also contain display settings, including the page display layout and zoom level in a Viewer Preferences object.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Adobe Reader uses these settings to override the user's default settings when opening the document.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The free Adobe Reader cannot remove these settings.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] PDF files can be created specifically to be accessible to people with disabilities.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] PDF file formats in use as of 2014 can include tags, text equivalents, captions, audio descriptions, and more.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Some software can automatically produce tagged PDFs, but this feature is not always enabled by default.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Leading screen readers, including JAWS, Window-Eyes, Hal, and Kurzweil 1000 and 3000 can read tagged PDFs.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Moreover, tagged PDFs can be re-flowed and magnified for readers with visual impairments.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Adding tags to older PDFs and those that are generated from scanned documents can present some challenges.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] One of the significant challenges with PDF accessibility is that PDF documents have three distinct views, which, depending on the document's creation, can be inconsistent with each other.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The three views are (i) the physical view, (ii) the tags view, and (iii) the content view.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The physical view is displayed and printed (what most people consider a PDF document).
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The tags view is what screen readers and other assistive technologies use to deliver high-quality navigation and reading experience to users with disabilities.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The content view is based on the physical order of objects within the PDF's content stream and may be displayed by software that does not fully support the tags' view, such as the Reflow feature in Adobe's Reader.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] PDF/UA, the International Standard for accessible PDF based on ISO 32000-1 was first published as ISO 14289–1 in 2012 and establishes normative language for accessible PDF technology.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] PDF/UA addresses accessibility of the PDF format it brings the ideas behind WCAG 2.0 to establish PDF-specific accessibility rules.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] AcroForms were introduced in the PDF 1.2 format.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] AcroForms permit the uses of objects (*e.g.* text boxes, Radio buttons, *etc.*) and some code (*e.g.* JavaScript).
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Alongside the standard PDF action types, interactive forms (AcroForms) support submitting, resetting, and importing data.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The "submit" action transmits the names and values of selected interactive form fields to a specified uniform resource locator (URL).
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] based on PDF, uses the same syntax and has essentially the same file structure, but is much simpler than PDF since the body of an FDF document consists of only one required object.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Forms Data Format is defined in the PDF specification (since PDF 1.2).
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The Forms Data Format can be used when submitting form data to a server, receiving the response, and incorporating it into the interactive form.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] It can also be used to export form data to stand-alone files that can be imported back into the corresponding PDF interactive form.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] FDF was originally defined in 1996 as part of ISO 32000-2:2017.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] (external XML Forms Data Format Specification, Version 2.0; supported since PDF 1.5; it replaced the "XML" form submission format defined in PDF 1.4) the XML version of Forms Data Format, but the XFDF implements only a subset of FDF containing forms and annotations.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Some entries in the FDF dictionary do not have XFDF equivalents – such as the Status, Encoding, JavaScript, Page's keys, EmbeddedFDFs, Differences, and Target.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] In addition, XFDF does not allow the spawning, or addition, of new pages based on the given data; as can be done when using an FDF file.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The XFDF specification is referenced (but not included) in PDF 1.5 specification (and in later versions).
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The PDF 1.4 specification allowed form submissions in XML format, but this was replaced by submissions in XFDF format in the PDF 1.5 specification.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] XFDF can be used in the same way as FDF; e.g., form data is submitted to a server, modifications are made, then sent back and the new form data is imported in an interactive form.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] This standard is a normative reference of ISO 32000-2.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The entire document can be submitted rather than individual fields and values, as was defined in PDF 1.4.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] AcroForms can keep form field values in external stand-alone files containing key-value pairs.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The external files may use Forms Data Format (FDF) and XML Forms Data Format (XFDF) files.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The usage rights (UR) signatures define rights for import form data files in FDF, XFDF, and text (CSV/TSV) formats, and export form data files in FDF and XFDF formats.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] In PDF 1.5, Adobe Systems introduced a proprietary format for forms; Adobe XML Forms Architecture (XFA).
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Adobe XFA Forms are not compatible with ISO 32000's AcroForms feature, and most PDF processors do not handle XFA content.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The XFA specification is referenced from ISO 32000-1/PDF 1.7 as an external proprietary specification and was entirely deprecated from PDF with ISO 32000-2 (PDF 2.0).
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Anyone may create applications that can read and write PDF files without having to pay royalties to Adobe Systems.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Adobe holds patents to PDF, but licenses them for royalty-free use in developing software complying with its PDF specification.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] In November 2019, researchers from Ruhr University Bochum and Hackmanit GmbH published attacks on digitally signed PDFs.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] They showed how to change the visible content in a signed PDF without invalidating the signature in 21 of 22 desktop PDF viewers and 6 of 8 online validation services by abusing implementation flaws.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] At the same conference, they additionally showed how to exfiltrate the plaintext of encrypted content in PDFs.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] In 2021, they showed new so-called *shadow attacks* on PDFs that abuse the flexibility of features provided in the specification.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] An overview of security issues in PDFs regarding denial of service, information disclosure, data manipulation, and arbitrary code execution attacks was presented by Jens Müller.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Some popular PDF readers have a history of security vulnerabilities that allows PDF files that have been infected with viruses, Trojans, and other malware to inflict damage.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Such PDF files can have hidden JavaScript code that might exploit vulnerabilities in a PDF reader, hidden objects executed when the file that hides them is opened, and, less commonly, a malicious PDF can launch malware.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] PDF attachments carrying viruses were first discovered in 2001.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The virus, named *OUTLOOK.PDFWorm* or *Peachy*, uses Microsoft Outlook to send itself as an attached Adobe PDF file.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] It was activated with Adobe Acrobat, but not with Acrobat Reader.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Over the years, several vulnerabilities have been discovered in various versions of Adobe Reader, which prompted the company to issue security fixes.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Vulnerabilities have been discovered in other PDF readers as well.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] One aggravating factor is that a PDF reader can be configured to start automatically if a web page has an embedded PDF file, providing a vector for attack.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] If a malicious web page contains an infected PDF file that takes advantage of a vulnerability in the PDF reader, the system may be compromised even if the browser is secure.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Some of these vulnerabilities are a result of badly written PDF readers mishandling JavaScript embedded in the PDF file.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Disabling JavaScript execution in the PDF reader can help mitigate such future exploits, although it does not protect against exploits in other parts of the PDF viewing software.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Some security experts say that JavaScript is not essential for a PDF reader and that the security benefit that comes from disabling JavaScript outweighs any compatibility issues caused.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] One way of avoiding PDF file exploits is to have a local or web service convert files to another format before viewing.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] On March 30, 2010, security researcher Didier Stevens reported an Adobe Reader and Foxit Reader exploit that runs a malicious executable if the user allows it to launch when asked.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] PDF streams can have nested filters, which allows one to craft a 5 kilobyte file that unpacks to 1 petabyte in RAM.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] This can be used to cause a denial of service with implementations that don't guard against this like it was the case with pypdf's CVE-2025-55197.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Many PDF viewers are provided free of charge from a variety of sources.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Programs to manipulate and edit PDF files are available, usually for purchase.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Additionally, most modern web browsers, including Chrome, Firefox, and Safari, include PDF viewing capabilities, replacing browser plugins that were previously created for such purposes.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] There are many software options for creating PDFs, including the PDF printing capabilities built into macOS, iOS, and most Linux distributions.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Much document processing software including LibreOffice, Microsoft Office 2007 (if updated to SP2) and later, WordPerfect 9, and Scribus can export documents in PDF.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Google's online office suite Google Docs allows uploading and saving to PDF.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Some web apps offer free PDF editing and annotation tools.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The Free Software Foundation was "developing a free, high-quality and fully functional set of libraries and programs that implement the PDF file format and associated technologies to the ISO 32000 standard", as one of its high priority projects.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] In 2011, however, the GNU PDF project was removed from the list of "high priority projects" due to the maturation of the Poppler library, which has enjoyed wider use in applications such as Evince with the GNOME desktop environment.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] There are also commercial development libraries available as listed in List of PDF software.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The Apache PDFBox project of the Apache Software Foundation is an open source Java library, licensed under the Apache License, for working with PDF documents.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Raster image processors (RIPs) are used to convert PDF files into a raster format suitable for imaging onto paper and other media in printers, digital production presses and prepress in a process known as rasterization.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] RIPs capable of processing PDF directly include the Adobe PDF Print Engine from Adobe Systems and Jaws and the Harlequin RIP from Global Graphics.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] In 1993, the Jaws raster image processor from Global Graphics became the first shipping prepress RIP that interpreted PDF natively without conversion to another format.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The company released an upgrade to its Harlequin RIP with the same capability in 1997.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Agfa-Gevaert introduced and shipped Apogee, the first prepress workflow system based on PDF, in 1997.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Many commercial offset printers have accepted the submission of press-ready PDF files as a print source, specifically the PDF/X-1a subset and variations of the same.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The submission of press-ready PDF files is a replacement for the problematic need for receiving collected native working files.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] In 2006, PDF was widely accepted as the standard print job format at the Open Source Development Labs Printing Summit.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] It is supported as a print job format by the Common Unix Printing System and desktop application projects such as GNOME, KDE, Firefox, Thunderbird, LibreOffice and OpenOffice have switched to emit print jobs in PDF.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Some desktop printers also support direct PDF printing, which can interpret PDF data without external help.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] PDF was selected as the "native" metafile format for macOS (originally called Mac OS X), replacing the PICT format of the earlier classic Mac OS.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The imaging model of the Quartz graphics layer is based on the model common to Display PostScript and PDF, leading to the nickname *Display PDF*.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The Preview application can display PDF files, as can version 2.0 and later of the Safari web browser.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] System-level support for PDF allows macOS applications to create PDF documents automatically, provided they support the OS-standard printing architecture.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The files are then exported in PDF 1.3 format according to the file header.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] When taking a screenshot under Mac OS X versions 10.0 through 10.3, the image was also captured as a PDF; later versions save screen captures as a PNG file, though this behavior can be set back to PDF if desired.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Adobe Acrobat is one example of proprietary software that allows the user to annotate, highlight, and add notes to already created PDF files.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] One UNIX application available as free software (under the GNU General Public License) is PDFedit.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The freeware Foxit Reader, available for Microsoft Windows, macOS and Linux, allows annotating documents.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Tracker Software's PDF-XChange Viewer allows annotations and markups without restrictions in its freeware alternative.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Apple's macOS's integrated PDF viewer, Preview, does also enable annotations as does the open-source software Skim, with the latter supporting interaction with LaTeX, SyncTeX, and PDFSync and integration with BibDesk reference management software.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Freeware Qiqqa can create an annotation report that summarizes all the annotations and notes one has made across their library of PDFs.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The Text Verification Tool exports differences in documents as annotations and markups.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] There are also web annotation systems that support annotation in pdf and other document formats.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] In cases where PDFs are expected to have all of the functionality of paper documents, ink annotation is required.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Numerous tools and source code libraries support these tasks.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Several labeled datasets to test PDF conversion and information extraction tools exist and have been used for benchmark evaluations of the tool's performance.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] The Open XML Paper Specification is a competing format used both as a page description language and as the native print spooler format for Microsoft Windows since Windows Vista.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] Mixed Object: Document Content Architecture is a competing format.
[src:postscript-lang/portable-document-format] MO:DCA-P is a part of Advanced Function Presentation.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Type 1 and Type 3 fonts, though introduced by Adobe in 1984 as part of the PostScript page description language, did not see widespread use until March 1985, when the first laser printer to use the PostScript language, the Apple LaserWriter, was introduced.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Even then, in 1985, the outline fonts were resident only in the printer, and the screen used bitmap fonts as substitutes for outline fonts.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Although originally part of PostScript, Type 1 fonts used a simplified set of drawing operations compared to ordinary PostScript (programmatic elements such as loops and variables were removed, much like PDF), but Type 1 fonts added *hints* to help low-resolution rendering.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Originally, Adobe kept the details of their hinting scheme undisclosed and used a (simple) encryption scheme to protect Type 1 outlines and hints, which still persists today (although the encryption scheme and key have since been published by Adobe).
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Despite these measures, Adobe's scheme was quickly reverse-engineered by other players in the industry.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Adobe nevertheless required anyone working with Type 1 fonts to license their technology.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Type 3 fonts allowed for all the sophistication of the PostScript language, but without the standardized approach to hinting (though some companies, such as ATF, implemented their own proprietary schemes) or an encryption scheme.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Other differences further added to the confusion.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] The cost of the licensing was considered very high at this time, and Adobe continued to stonewall on more attractive rates.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] It was this issue that led Apple to design their own system, TrueType, around 1991.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Immediately following the announcement of TrueType, Adobe published ”Adobe type 1 font format”, a detailed specification for the format.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Font development tools such as Fontographer added the ability to create Type 1 fonts.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] The Type 2 format has since been used as one basis for the modern OpenType Format.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] In the PostScript (PS) language glyphs are described with cubic Bézier curves (as opposed to the quadratic curves of TrueType), and thus a single set of glyphs can be resized through simple mathematical transformations performed in a PostScript raster image processor such as in a PostScript printer.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Because the data of Type 1 is a description of the outline of a glyph and not a raster image (i.e. a bitmap), Type 1 fonts are commonly referred to as *outline* fonts as opposed to *bitmap*, or *screen*, fonts.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Bitmap versions of outline fonts were used on-screen, but bitmap fonts aligned with the pixels of screens, not the higher-resolution grids of printers and imagesetters, causing differences in letter spacing, line wraps, and other copy-fitting issues.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Print dialogs included an option to mitigate this discrepancy by printing at 96% size, fitting each screen pixel to an integral number of print pixels.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Type 0 is a *composite* font format—as described in the PostScript Language Reference Manual, 2nd Edition.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] A composite font is composed of a high-level font that references multiple descendant fonts.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Type 1 (also known as ***PostScript***, ***PostScript Type 1***, ***PS1***, ***T1*** or ***Adobe Type 1***) is the font format for single-byte digital fonts for use with Adobe Type Manager software and with PostScript printers.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] It was originally a proprietary specification, but Adobe released the specification to third-party font manufacturers provided that all Type 1 fonts adhere to it.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Type 1 fonts are natively supported in macOS, and in Windows 2000 and later via the GDI API.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Adobe announced on 27 January 2021 that they would end support for Type 1 fonts in Adobe products after January 2023.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Support for Type 1 fonts in Adobe Photoshop was discontinued with the release of version 23.0 of the product in October 2021.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Type 2 is a character string format that offers a compact representation of the character description procedures in an outline font file.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] The format is designed to be used with the Compact Font Format (CFF).
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] The CFF/Type2 format is the basis for Type 1 OpenType fonts, and is used for embedding fonts in Acrobat 3.0 PDF files (PDF format version 1.2).
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Type 3 font (also known as ***PostScript Type 3*** or ***PS3***, ***T3*** or ***Adobe Type 3***) consists of glyphs defined using the full PostScript language, rather than just a subset.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Because of this, a Type 3 font can do some things that Type 1 fonts cannot do, such as specify shading, color, and fill patterns.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Adobe Type Manager did not support Type 3 fonts, and they are not supported as native WYSIWYG fonts on any version of macOS or Windows.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Type 4 is a format that was used to make fonts for printer font cartridges and for permanent storage on a printer's hard disk.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] The character descriptions are expressed in the Type 1 format.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Adobe does not document this proprietary format.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Type 5 is similar to the Type 4 format but is used for fonts stored in the ROMs of PostScript printers, also known as *compressed ROM* (*CROM*) fonts.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Ghostscript referred them as CID font types 0, 1, and 2 respectively, documented in Adobe supplements.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Types 9, 10, and 11 are CID-keyed fonts for storing Types 1, 3, and 42, respectively.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Type 14, or the Chameleon font format, is used to represent a large number of fonts in a small amount of storage space such as printer ROM.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] The core set of Chameleon fonts consists of one Master Font, and a set of font descriptors that specify how the Master Font is to be adjusted to give the desired set of character shapes for a specific typeface.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Adobe does not document the Type 14 format.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] It was introduced with PostScript 3 in 1997, and de-emphasized in later years as storage became cheaper.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Type 32 is used for downloading bitmap fonts to PostScript interpreters with version number 2016 or greater.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] The bitmap characters are transferred directly into the interpreter's font cache, thus saving space in the printer's memory.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] The Type 42 font format is a PostScript wrapper around a TrueType font, allowing PostScript-capable printers containing a TrueType rasterizer (which was first implemented in PostScript interpreter version 2010 as an optional feature, later standard) to print TrueType fonts.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Support for multibyte CJK TrueType fonts was added in PostScript version 2015.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] The out-of-sequence choice of the number 42 is said to be a jesting reference to *The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy*, where 42 is the Answer to Life, the Universe, and Everything.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] In addition to font types, PostScript specifications also defined the Core Font Set, which dictates the minimum number of fonts, and character sets to be supported by each font.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] PostScript Level 2 defined 35 font styles which form 10 type families.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Many computer operating systems have these fonts installed, while various projects have created clones of them.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] For instance, the Ghostscript fonts (also known as the URW Base 35 fonts) are open-source clones of all fonts defined in PostScript 2.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] In PostScript 3, 136 font styles are specified, which include the 35 font styles defined in PostScript 2, core fonts in popular operating systems (namely Windows 95, Windows NT, and Macintosh), selected fonts from Microsoft Office, and the HP 110 font set.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] In PDF, 14 Type 1 fonts are defined as the standard fonts.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] They include the 13 font styles defined by PostScript Level 1, along with ITC Zapf Dingbats.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] However, in recent versions of Adobe Acrobat Reader, Helvetica and Times were internally replaced by Arial and Times New Roman respectively.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Although PostScript fonts can contain any character set, there are character sets specifically developed by Adobe, which are used by fonts developed by Adobe.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] It includes a basic character set containing upper and lowercase letters, figures, accented characters, and punctuation.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Compared to the ISO-Adobe character set, Western 2 also adds 17 additional symbol characters: euro, litre, estimated, omega, pi, partialdiff, delta, product, summation, radical, infinity, integral, approxequal, notequal, lessequal, greaterequal, and lozenge.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Fonts with an Adobe Western 2 character set support most western languages including Afrikaans, Basque, Breton, Catalan, Danish, Dutch, English, Finnish, French, Gaelic, German, Icelandic, Indonesian, Irish, Italian, Norwegian, Portuguese, Sami, Spanish, Swahili and Swedish.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] This standard superseded ISO-Adobe as the new minimum character set standard as implemented in OpenType fonts from Adobe.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Fonts with an Adobe CE character set also include the characters necessary to support the following central European languages: Croatian, Czech, Estonian, Hungarian, Latvian, Lithuanian, Polish, Romanian, Serbian (Latin), Slovak, Slovenian and Turkish.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Supported encodings include ISO-2022, EUC-CN, GBK, UCS-2, UTF-8, UTF-16, UTF-32, and the mixed one, two- and four-byte encoding as published in GB 18030-2005.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] This Traditional Chinese character collection provides support for the Big-5 and CNS 11643-1992 character set standards.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] It also includes support for a number of extensions to Big-5, which contain characters used mainly in the Hong Kong locale.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Primary supported Big-5 extensions include HKSCS.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Supported encodings include ISO-2022, EUC-TW, Big Five, UCS-2, UTF-8, UTF-16, and UTF-32.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] In Adobe-CNS1-7, 23 additional glyphs were added, with 25 additional mappings for its Unicode CMap resources.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] It is a series of character sets developed for Japanese fonts.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Adobe's latest, the Adobe-Japan1-6 set covers character sets from JIS X 0208, ISO-2022-JP, Microsoft Windows 3.1 J, JIS X 0213:2004, JIS X 0212-1990, Kyodo News U-PRESS character set.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] It was originally as an implementation of JIS X 0212-1990 character set standard and the Macintosh extensions, but with the introduction of Adobe-Japan1 supplement 6 (Adobe-Japan1-6) standard, Adobe-Japan2-0 became obsolete.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] This Korean character collection provides support for the KS X 1001:1992 and KS X 1003:1992 character set standards, and their selected corporate variations.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Supported encodings include ISO-2022-KR, EUC-KR, Johab, UHC, UCS-2, UTF-8, UTF-16, and UTF-32.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Fonts with an ISO-Adobe character set support most western languages including: Afrikaans, Basque, Breton, Catalan, Danish, Dutch, English, Finnish, French, Gaelic, German, Icelandic, Indonesian, Irish, Italian, Norwegian, Portuguese, Sami, Spanish, Swahili and Swedish.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] This is the standard character set in most PostScript Type 1 fonts from Adobe.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] The **CID-keyed font** (also known as ***CID font***, ***CID-based font***, short for ***Character Identifier font***) is a font structure, originally developed for PostScript font formats, designed to address a large number of glyphs.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] It was developed to support pictographic East Asian character sets, as these comprise many more characters than the Latin, Greek and Cyrillic writing systems.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Adobe developed CID-keyed font formats to solve problems with the OCF/Type 0 format, for addressing complex Asian-language (CJK) encoding and very large character sets.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] CID-keyed internals can be used with the Type 1 font format for standard CID-keyed fonts, or Type 2 for CID-keyed OpenType fonts.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] CID-keyed fonts often reference "character collections," static glyph sets defined for different language coverage purposes.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Although in principle any font maker may define character collections, Adobe's are the only ones in wide usage.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Each character collection has an encoding which maps Character IDs to glyphs.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Each member glyph in a character collection is identified by a unique character identifier (CID).
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Such CIDs are generally supplemental to other encodings or mappings such as Unicode.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Character collections are uniquely named by registry, ordering and supplement, such as "Adobe-Japan1-6." The registry is the developer (such as Adobe).
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] The so-called "ordering" gives the purpose of the collection (for example, "Japan1").
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] The supplement number (such as 6) indicates incremental additions: for a given language, there may be multiple character collections of increasing size, each a superset of the last, using a higher supplement number.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] The Adobe-Japan1-0 collection is 8284 glyphs, while Adobe-Japan1-6 is 23,058 glyphs.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] CID-keyed fonts may be made without reference to a character collection by using an "identity" encoding, such as Identity-H (for horizontal writing) or Identity-V (for vertical).
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Such fonts may each have a unique character set, and in such cases the CID number of a glyph is not informative; generally the Unicode encoding is used instead, potentially with supplemental information.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] CID-keyed fonts internally have their character sets divided into "rows," with the advantage that each row may have different global hinting parameters applied.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] In theory it would be possible to make CID-keyed OpenType versions of western fonts.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] This would seem desirable for some such fonts because of the hinting advantages.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] However, according to Adobe, much of the software infrastructure (applications, drivers, operating systems) makes incorrect assumptions about CID-keyed fonts in ways that makes such fonts behave badly in real-world usage.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Adobe **ClearScan** technology (as from Acrobat 9 Pro) creates custom **Type1-CID** fonts to match the visual appearance of a scanned document after optical character recognition (OCR).
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] ClearScan does not replace the fonts with system fonts or substitute them by Type1-MM (as in Acrobat 8 and earlier versions), but uses these newly created custom fonts.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] The custom fonts are embedded in the PDF file (this is mandatory).
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] In Acrobat DC, it is no longer called "ClearScan" but instead "Recognize Text - Editable Text & Images", and it is now possible to edit the text.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] The so-called PostScript or Type 1 flavor of OpenType fonts, also called OpenType CFF, contains glyph outlines and hints in a CFF table.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] CFF fonts can be embedded in PDF files, starting with PDF version 1.2.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] It is the usual approach to representing a Type 1 font within PDF.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] CID-keyed fonts can be represented within CFF with Type 2 charstrings for CID-keyed OpenType fonts.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] A Type 1 font can be losslessly converted into CFF/Type2 format and back.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] PostScript glyph data can be embedded in OpenType font files, but OpenType fonts are not limited to using PostScript outlines.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] PostScript outlines in OpenType fonts are encoded in the Type2 Compact Font Format (CFF).
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] When Adobe converted PostScript Type 1 and Type 1 multiple master fonts to OpenType CFF format, they were made based on the last Type 1/MM versions from the Adobe Type Library fonts.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] For many Adobe Originals fonts, particularly those designed by Robert Slimbach, Adobe did some degree of redesign along with the conversion to OpenType.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] The typeface Helvetica Narrow was not converted to OpenType, because the Type 1 original was a mathematically squished version of Helvetica, rather than an actually designed condensed typeface.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] This was originally done to conserve ROM space in PostScript printers.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] As a result of the above changes, Adobe no longer guarantees metric compatibility between Type 1 and OpenType fonts.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Adobe then developed the CID-keyed font file format which was designed to offer better performance and a more flexible architecture for addressing the complex Asian-language encoding and character set issues.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Adobe does not document or support OCF font format.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] OCF font metrics are described in Adobe Composite Font Metrics file.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] An AFM file provides both global metrics for a font program and the metrics of each individual character.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] The metrics of a multiple master font are described by one AMFM file, which specifies the control data and global font information, plus one AFM file for each of the master designs in the font.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] An ACFM file provides information about the structure of a composite font.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Specifically, the global metrics of the composite font program and the global metrics of each of its immediately descendent font programs.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] ACFM file does not associate with a base font, but act as the top-level structure of a composite font.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] The character metrics of individual characters in the composite font are described completely by one of more associated AFM files.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] The formats are sufficiently similar that a compliant parser can parse AFM, ACFM, and AMFM files.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Though these files syntactically can contain arbitrary PostScript code, they usually follow a rather rigid formula in order to allow readers that are less than full PostScript interpreters to process them (for example to subset the font).
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] The last two operators in the clear text portion are `currentfile eexec` (encrypted exec), which instructs the interpreter to switch to reading the current file as an encrypted stream of instructions.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] The data structures created here are marked `noaccess` to make them inaccessible for subsequent PostScript code.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] The final action in the encrypted portion is to switch back to reading the file normally, but since eexec would read ahead a bit it was impossible to know at exactly which character normal processing would resume.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Therefore, PFA files end with a trailer of 512 zeroes followed by a `cleartomark` operator that throws away any operands that might have ended up on the stack as a result of interpreting those zeroes starting from a random position.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] The PFB format is a lightweight wrapper to allow more compact storage of the data in a PFA file.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] The file consists of a number of blocks, each of which is marked as ASCII or binary.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] To recreate the corresponding PFA file, one takes the ASCII blocks verbatim and hex-encodes the binary blocks.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] The binary blocks are those which make up the encrypted portion of the font program.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] `LWFN` is the file type code for this kind of file.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Palatino-BoldItalic would thus be found in the file PalatBolIta.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] The PFM format is documented in the Windows 3.1 "*Printers and Fonts Kit*" help file (PFK31WH.HLP).
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Some details are also covered in the Windows 3.1 "*Device Drivers Adaptation Guide*" help file (DDAG31WH.HLP).
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Both of those documents are part of the Windows 3.1 Device Development Kit (DDK), which is still available (October 2008) to MSDN subscribers.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Windows 95, Windows 98, Windows NT 4 and Windows Me do not support Type 1 fonts natively.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Adobe Type Manager is needed in order to use these fonts on these operating systems.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Windows 2000, Windows XP and Windows Vista support Type 1 fonts natively through GDI calls.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] The Windows Presentation Foundation introduced in Windows Vista, which is also available for Windows XP however drops support for Type 1 fonts, in favor of Type 2 fonts.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] For Microsoft Windows platforms that natively support PostScript, only binary PostScript and OpenType file formats are supported.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript-fonts] Windows Presentation Foundation (formerly codenamed Avalon) in Windows Vista supports rasterizing OpenType CFF/Type 2 fonts, whereas Type 1 fonts will still be supported in GDI, but not in GDI+.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] The concepts of the PostScript language were seeded in 1976 by John Gaffney at Evans & Sutherland, a computer graphics company.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] At that time, Gaffney and John Warnock were developing an interpreter for a large three-dimensional graphics database of New York Harbor.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Concurrently, researchers at Xerox PARC had developed the first laser printer and had recognized the need for a standard means of defining page images.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] In 1975–76 Bob Sproull and William Newman developed the Press format, which was eventually used in the Xerox Star system to drive laser printers.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] But Press, a data format rather than a language, lacked flexibility, and PARC mounted the Interpress effort to create a successor.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] In 1978, John Gaffney and Martin Newell then at Xerox PARC wrote J & M or JaM (for "John and Martin") which was used for VLSI design and the investigation of type and graphics printing.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] This work later evolved and expanded into the Interpress language.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Warnock left with Chuck Geschke and founded Adobe Systems in December 1982.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] They, together with Doug Brotz, Ed Taft and Bill Paxton created a simpler language, similar to Interpress, called PostScript, which went on the market in 1984.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Meanwhile, in the spring of 1983, Steve Jobs came to visit Adobe and was dazzled by PostScript's potential, especially for the new Macintosh computer he was developing at Apple.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] To John Sculley's frustration, Jobs licensed the PostScript technology from Adobe by offering a $1.5 million advance against PostScript royalties, plus $2.5 million in exchange for 20 percent of Adobe shares.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] During a series of meetings in 1983, Jobs also repeatedly offered for Apple to buy Adobe outright, but the founders kept turning him down.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] In December 1983, the two companies finally signed off on the PostScript licensing deal, and Adobe had to shift focus immediately from high-end, high-resolution printing devices to the consumer-oriented Apple LaserWriter laser printer.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] In response, Warnock and Brotz solved the so-called "appearance problem" of making the stem width of letters scale properly so that they look good at all resolutions.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Their breakthrough was so important that Adobe never patented the technology, in order to keep its details concealed as a trade secret.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Many years later, Warnock revealed the trade secret in a 2010 lecture, and in 2022, Adobe publicly released an early version of PostScript's original source code from February 1984.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Paxton worked on several other related improvements, such as font hinting.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] This work occurred after February 1984, meaning that Paxton's improvements were not included in the source code release and are still protected as trade secrets.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Adobe was also responsible for porting PostScript to the Canon's Motorola 68000 chip.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Apple and Adobe announced the LaserWriter at Apple's annual stockholder meeting on January 23, 1985.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] It was the first printer to ship with PostScript, sparking the desktop publishing (DTP) revolution in the mid-1980s.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] The original PostScript royalty was five percent of the list price for each laser printer sold, which was $350 of the original LaserWriter list price of $6,995, and such royalties provided nearly all of Adobe's income during its early years.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] (Apple later renegotiated the contract to pay a licensing fee based on volume of printers shipped.) The combination of technical merits and widespread availability made PostScript the language of choice for graphical output for printing applications.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] An interpreter (sometimes referred to as a RIP for Raster Image Processor) for the PostScript language was a common component of laser printers during the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] However, the cost of implementation was high; computers output raw PS code that would be interpreted by the printer into a raster image at the printer's natural resolution.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] This required high-performance microprocessors and ample memory.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] The LaserWriter used a 12 MHz Motorola 68000, making it faster than any of the Macintosh computers to which it was attached.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] By 1987, the cost of licensing PS and fonts from Adobe was $400 to $900 per printer.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] When the laser printer engines themselves cost over a thousand dollars, the added cost of PS was marginal.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] But, as printer mechanisms fell in price, the cost of implementing PS became too great a fraction of overall printer cost.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] In addition, with desktop computers becoming more powerful during the 1990s than their attached printers, it no longer made sense to offload the rasterization work onto the resource-constrained printer.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] By 2001, few low-end printer models came with onboard support for PostScript, largely due to growing competition from much cheaper non-PostScript inkjet printers, and new software-based methods to render PostScript images on computers, making them suitable for any printer.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] PDF, a descendant of PostScript, provides one such method, and has largely replaced PostScript as the *de facto* standard for electronic document distribution.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] On high-end printers, PostScript processors remain common, and their use can dramatically reduce the CPU work involved in printing documents, transferring the work of rendering PostScript images from the computer to the printer.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] The first version of the PostScript language was released to the market in 1984.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] The qualifier *Level 1* was added when *Level 2* was introduced.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Prior to the introduction of Interpress and PostScript, printers were designed to print character output given the text—typically in ASCII—as input.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] There were a number of technologies for this task, but most shared the property that the glyphs were physically difficult to change, as they were stamped onto typewriter keys, bands of metal, or optical plates.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] This changed to some degree with the increasing popularity of dot matrix printers.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] The characters on these systems were drawn as a series of dots, as defined by a font table inside the printer.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] As they grew in sophistication, dot matrix printers started including several built-in fonts from which the user could select, and some models allowed users to upload their own custom glyphs into the printer.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Dot matrix printers also introduced the ability to print raster graphics.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] The graphics were interpreted by the computer and sent as a series of dots to the printer using a series of escape sequences.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] These printer control languages varied from printer to printer, requiring program authors to create numerous drivers.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Vector graphics printing was left to special-purpose devices, called plotters.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Almost all plotters shared a common command language, HPGL, but were of limited use for anything other than printing graphics.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] In addition, they tended to be expensive and slow, and thus rare.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Laser printers combine the best features of both printers and plotters.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Like plotters, laser printers offer high-quality line art, and like dot-matrix printers, they are able to generate pages of text and raster graphics.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Unlike either printers or plotters, a laser printer makes it possible to position high-quality graphics and text on the same page.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] PostScript made it possible to fully exploit these characteristics by offering a single control language that could be used on any brand of printer.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] PostScript went beyond the typical printer control language and was a complete programming language of its own.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Many applications can transform a document into a PostScript program, the execution of which results in the original document.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] This program can be sent to an interpreter in a printer, which results in a printed document, or to one inside another application, which will display the document on-screen.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Since the document-program is the same regardless of its destination, it is called *device-independent*.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] PostScript is noteworthy for implementing on-the-fly rasterization in which everything, even text, is specified in terms of straight lines and cubic Bézier curves (previously found only in CAD applications), which allows arbitrary scaling, rotating and other transformations.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] When the PostScript program is interpreted, the interpreter converts these instructions into the dots needed to form the output.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] For this reason, PostScript interpreters are occasionally called PostScript raster image processors, or RIPs.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Almost as complex as PostScript itself is its handling of fonts.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] The font system uses the PS graphics primitives to draw glyphs as curves, which can then be rendered at any resolution.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] A number of typographic issues had to be considered with this approach.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] One issue is that fonts do not scale linearly at small sizes and features of the glyphs will become proportionally too large or small and start to look displeasing.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] PostScript avoided this problem with the inclusion of font hinting, in which additional information is provided in horizontal or vertical bands to help identify the features in each letter that are important for the rasterizer to maintain.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] The result was significantly better-looking fonts even at low resolution.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] It had formerly been believed that hand-tuned bitmap fonts were required for this task.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] At the time, the technology for including these hints in fonts was carefully guarded, and the hinted fonts were compressed and encrypted into what Adobe called a *Type 1 Font* (also known as *PostScript Type 1 Font*, *PS1*, *T1* or *Adobe Type 1*).
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Type 1 was effectively a simplification of the PS system to store outline information only, as opposed to being a complete language (PDF is similar in this regard).
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Adobe would then sell licenses to the Type 1 technology to those wanting to add hints to their own fonts.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Those who did not license the technology were left with the *Type 3 Font* (also known as *PostScript Type 3 Font*, *PS3* or *T3*).
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Type 3 fonts allowed for all the sophistication of the PostScript language, but without the standardized approach to hinting.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] The Type 2 font format was designed to be used with Compact Font Format (CFF) charstrings, and was implemented to reduce the overall font file size.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] The CFF/Type2 format later became the basis for handling PostScript outlines in OpenType fonts.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] The CID-keyed font format was also designed, to solve the problems in the OCF/Type 0 fonts, for addressing the complex Asian-language (CJK) encoding and very large character set issues.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] The CID-keyed font format can be used with the Type 1 font format for standard CID-keyed fonts, or Type 2 for CID-keyed OpenType fonts.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] To compete with Adobe's system, Apple designed their own system, TrueType, around 1991.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Immediately following the announcement of TrueType, Adobe published the specification for the Type 1 font format.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Retail tools such as Altsys Fontographer (acquired by Macromedia in January 1995, owned by FontLab since May 2005) added the ability to create Type 1 fonts.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Since then, many free Type 1 fonts have been released; for instance, the fonts used with the TeX typesetting system are available in this format.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] In the early 1990s, there were several other systems for storing outline-based fonts, developed by Bitstream and Metafont for instance, but none included a general-purpose printing solution and they were therefore not widely used.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] In the late 1990s, Adobe joined Microsoft in developing OpenType, essentially a functional superset of the Type 1 and TrueType formats.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] When printed to a PostScript output device, the unneeded parts of the OpenType font are omitted, and what is sent to the device by the driver is the same as it would be for a TrueType or Type 1 font, depending on which kind of outlines were present in the OpenType font.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Adobe supported Type 1 fonts in its products until January 2023, when it fully removed support in favor of OpenType fonts.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Both computer printers and high-end typesetters such as Linotronic implemented PostScript.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] In the 1980s, Adobe drew most of its revenue from the licensing fees for implementations, known as a raster image processor or *RIP*.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] As a number of new RISC-based platforms became available in the mid-1980s, some found Adobe's support of the new machines to be lacking.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] At one point, Microsoft licensed to Apple a PostScript-compatible interpreter it had bought called TrueImage, and Apple licensed to Microsoft its new font format, TrueType.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Apple ended up reaching an accord with Adobe and licensed genuine PostScript for its printers, but TrueType became the standard outline font technology for both Windows and the Macintosh.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Today, third-party PostScript-compatible interpreters are widely used in printers and multifunction peripherals (MFPs).
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] For example, CSR plc's IPS PS3 interpreter, formerly known as PhoenixPage, is standard in many printers and MFPs, including those developed by Hewlett-Packard and sold under the LaserJet and Color LaserJet lines.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Other third-party PostScript solutions used by print and MFP manufacturers include Jaws and the Harlequin RIP, both by Global Graphics.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] A free software version, with several other applications, is Ghostscript.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Several compatible interpreters are listed on the Undocumented Printing Wiki.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Some basic, inexpensive laser printers do not support PostScript, instead coming with drivers that simply rasterize the platform's native graphics formats rather than converting them to PostScript first.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] When PostScript support is needed for such a printer, Ghostscript can be used.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] There are also a number of commercial PostScript interpreters, such as TeleType Co.'s *T-Script* or Brother's *BR-Script3*.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] PostScript became commercially successful due to the introduction of the graphical user interface (GUI), allowing designers to directly lay out pages for eventual output on laser printers.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] However, the GUIs' own graphics systems were generally much less sophisticated than PostScript; Apple's QuickDraw, for instance, supported only basic lines and arcs, not the complex B-splines and advanced region filling options of PostScript.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] In order to take full advantage of PostScript printing, applications on the computers had to re-implement those features using the host platform's own graphics system.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] This led to numerous issues where the on-screen layout would not exactly match the printed output, due to differences in the implementation of these features.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] As computer power grew, it became possible to host the PS system in the computer rather than the printer.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] This led to the natural evolution of PS from a printing system to one that could also be used as the host's own graphics language.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] There were numerous advantages to this approach; not only did it help eliminate the possibility of different output on screen and printer, but it also provided a powerful graphics system for the computer, and allowed the printers to be "dumb" at a time when the cost of the laser engines was falling.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] In a production setting, using PostScript as a display system meant that the host computer could render low-resolution to the screen, higher resolution to the printer, or simply send the PS code to a smart printer for offboard printing.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] However, PostScript was written with printing in mind, and had numerous features that made it unsuitable for direct use in an interactive display system.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] In particular, PS was based on the idea of collecting up PS commands until the `showpage` command was seen, at which point all of the commands read up to that point were interpreted and output.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] In an interactive system, this was clearly not appropriate, nor did PS have any sort of interactivity built in; for example, supporting hit detection for mouse interactivity obviously did not apply when PS was being used on a printer.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] When Steve Jobs left Apple and started NeXT, he pitched Adobe on the idea of using PS as the display system for his new workstation computers.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] The result was Display PostScript, or DPS.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] DPS added basic functionality to improve performance by changing many string lookups into 32 bit integers, adding support for direct output with every command, and adding functions to allow the GUI to inspect the diagram.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Additionally, a set of "bindings" was provided to allow PS code to be called directly from the C programming language.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] NeXT used these bindings in their NeXTStep system to provide an object oriented graphics system.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Although DPS was written in conjunction with NeXT, Adobe sold it commercially and it was a common feature of most Unix workstations in the 1990s.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Sun Microsystems took another approach, creating NeWS.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Instead of DPS's concept of allowing PS to interact with C programs, NeWS instead extended PS into a language suitable for running the entire GUI of a computer.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Sun added a number of new commands for timers, mouse control, interrupts and other systems needed for interactivity, and added data structures and language elements to allow it to be completely object oriented internally.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] A complete GUI, three in fact, were written in NeWS and provided for a time on their workstations.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] However, the ongoing efforts to standardize the X11 system led to its introduction and widespread use on Sun systems, and NeWS never became widely used.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] PDF and PostScript share the same imaging model, and both formats are, mostly, mutually convertible to each other.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] However PostScript, the earlier format, lacks transparency: its native object model paints completely opaque.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Except this, both formats produce the same result when printed.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] But PDF lacks the general-purpose programming language framework of the PostScript language.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] A PDF document is a static data structure made for efficient access and embeds navigational information suitable for interactive viewing.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] PostScript is a Turing-complete programming language, belonging to the concatenative group of programming languages.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] It is an interpreted, stack-based language similar to Forth, with dynamic typing, data structures inspired by those found in Lisp, scoped memory and, since language level 2, garbage collection.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] The language syntax uses reverse Polish notation, which makes the order of operations unambiguous, but reading a program requires some practice, because one has to keep the layout of the stack in mind.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Most *operators* (what other languages term *functions*) take their arguments from the stack, and place their results onto the stack.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] *Literals* (for example, numbers) have the effect of placing a copy of themselves on the stack.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Sophisticated data structures can be built on the *array* and *dictionary* types, but cannot be declared to the type system, which sees them all only as arrays and dictionaries, so any further typing discipline to be applied to such user-defined "types" is left to the code that implements them.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] The character "%" is used to introduce comments in PostScript programs.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] As a convention, every PostScript program should start with the characters "%!PS" as an interpreter directive so that all devices will properly interpret it as PostScript.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] PostScript programs are typically divided into two parts, conventionally called the *prolog* and the *script*.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] The prolog contains procedures and is written by a programmer.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] The script passes data to those procedures.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] The script is often generated automatically, using a programming language other than PostScript.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] PostScript uses the point as its unit of length.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] However, unlike some of the other versions of the point, PostScript uses exactly 72 points to the inch.
[src:postscript-lang/postscript] Most implementations of PostScript use single-precision reals (24-bit mantissa), so it is not meaningful to use more than 9 decimal digits to specify a real number, and performing calculations may produce unacceptable round-off errors.
